1. Schedule Access Gate Rule

public.schedules is the single access gate for published schedule visibility.

If a user can read a schedule row through normal user-scoped access, they are considered authorized to open that schedule detail.

Do not add secondary owner-only gating in the schedule detail page using meetings.manager_id = auth.uid().

Do not reintroduce detail-page checks that block invited members after the schedule itself is already accessible.

2. Detail Data Fetch Rule

Schedule detail access must be validated first via normal user-scoped schedules query.

Only after schedule access is confirmed may additional supporting detail data be fetched.

Do not create new cross-table RLS dependencies between meetings and member_submissions.

Avoid policy recursion patterns where meetings policies depend on member_submissions while member_submissions policies also depend on meetings.

3. Member Schedule Regression Rule

Any change touching member dashboard navigation, current team context, token/memberId handling, or account/avatar state must preserve member published schedule visibility.

Invited members must continue to see the same published schedules already visible to the owner, subject to RLS.

Before finalizing any related change, verify:

owner schedule list still works

member schedule list still works

member schedule detail still works

4. Identity Source Consistency Rule

Avatar, display name, and initials for the same person must come from one stable identity source across owner and member surfaces.

Preferred order:

avatar_url

real display name

initials derived from real display name

? only as last resort

Never derive initials from:

"Member"

"Owner"

"Member of X"

helper copy, role labels, status text, or placeholder labels

5. Navbar Avatar Stability Rule

Do not render member navbar avatar from incomplete transient page state if a stable current-member object already exists.

Avoid brief fallback regressions such as ?, blank avatar, or wrong initials during route transitions.

Preserve the last known valid avatar / initials until fresh member data is ready.

Do not let Team / Schedule / Account pages use conflicting member identity sources.

6. Owner/Member UI Parity Rule

Shared concepts must behave consistently across owner and member dashboards unless intentionally different by product design.

Profile trigger/avatar behavior should remain visually and functionally aligned:

same active/highlight behavior

same fallback behavior

same identity source logic

Do not let owner and member navbars drift into separate inconsistent implementations unless explicitly required.

7. Stale Data Rule

If one surface shows updated avatar/name and another surface still shows stale data, treat it as a code/data-flow issue, not a database/RLS issue, unless proven otherwise.

Prefer fixing stale local/server data flow, refresh/revalidation, or incorrect object selection before touching Supabase policies.

8. Debug Cleanup Rule

Temporary debug logs, /api/dev/* routes, row-count inspectors, auth/session debug prints, and test-only UI must be removed after the issue is confirmed fixed.

Do not leave temporary debug artifacts in production code unless explicitly approved.

9. No Symptom-Masking Rule

Do not “fix” identity bugs by replacing wrong initials with "?" unless no real identity data exists.

Root cause must be traced to the actual source field, object selection, fallback chain, or stale state.

Hiding incorrect values is not considered a full fix.

10. Required Regression Checks After Related Changes

Any change touching:

member dashboard

account/profile

avatar rendering

team context

schedule page

schedule detail
must confirm all of the following still work:

owner can create a team

owner can publish a schedule

owner sees published schedule list

invited member sees published schedule list

invited member opens schedule detail

owner and member both show consistent avatar/name

owner sees member’s latest updated avatar/name

member account/profile card and navbar stay in sync
